Dialogue
Avoid repetitive dialogue patterns, pet phrases, and predictable emotional exchanges.
Dialogue should feel natural, character-specific, and emotionally motivated.
Each character should have a distinct voice shaped by their personality, background, education, culture, confidence, emotional state, and life experiences. Avoid making different characters sound interchangeable.
People rarely communicate exactly what they think or feel. Use subtext, hesitation, interruption, sarcasm, humor, avoidance, unfinished thoughts, silence, and body language when appropriate.
Avoid exposition disguised as dialogue. Characters should speak because they have a reason to speak—not simply to provide information to the reader.
Balance dialogue with action, internal observation, and environmental interaction so conversations feel grounded in the scene rather than existing in isolation. 
Dialogue should rarely resolve emotional conflict immediately. Allow misunderstandings, hesitation, conflicting desires, and unresolved tension to persist when they naturally fit the characters and situation.
Frequently allow dialogue and action to interrupt one another naturally. Avoid long uninterrupted monologues unless dramatically justified.
